  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Moses gave the Manassites the land which was conquered by them; in fact, the whole of the kingdom of Bashan, including not only the province of Bashan, but the northern half of Gilead (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:33-34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Of this the sons of Machir received Gilead, the modern Jebel Ajlun, between the Jabbok (Zerka) and the Mandhur (Hieromax, Jarmuk), because they had taken it and driven out the Amorites and destroyed them (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The imperfects in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are to be understood in the sense of pluperfects, the different parts being linked together by w consec. according to the simple style of the Semitic historical writings explained in the note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the leading thought being preceded by the clauses which explain it, instead of their being logically subordinated to it. \"The sons of Machir went to Gilead and took it...and Moses gave,\" etc., instead of \"Moses gave Gilead to the sons of Machir, who had gone thither and taken it...\" The words בּהּ ויּשׁב, \"Machir dwelt therein (in Gilead),\" do not point to a later period than the time of Moses, but simply state that the Machirites took possession of Gilead. As soon as Moses had given them the conquered land for their possession, they no doubt brought their families, like the Gadites and Reubenites, and settled them in fortified towns, that they might dwell there in safety, whilst the fighting men helped the other tribes to conquer Canaan. ישׁב signifies not merely \"to dwell,\" but literally to place oneself, or settle down (e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), and is even applied to the temporary sojourn of the Israelites in particular encampments (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 20:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - Machir (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 32:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): for the sons of Machir, or Machirites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But as Gilead does not mean the whole of the land with this name, but only the northern half, so the sons of Machir are not the whole of his posterity, but simply those who formed the family of Machirites which bore its father's name (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., the seven fathers' houses or divisions of the family, the heads of which are named in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 5:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The other descendants of Machir through Gilead, who formed the six families of Gilead mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:29-33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", received their inheritance in Canaan proper (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]